#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "Learning vi -- the \"cheatsheet\" technique"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:18
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide will teach you how to use vi, using a cheat sheet method to\n"
"accelerate the learning process. This will be the first guide for vi,\n"
"catering to beginners.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "Getting Started"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:33
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This tutorial will show you how to use vi, a powerful visual editor.\n"
"Using a special accelerated <e>cheat sheet</e> method, this tutorial is\n"
"designed to make you a proficient vi user without requiring a huge\n"
"time commitment. In this vi tutorial, you'll learn how to move\n"
"around, edit text, use insert mode, copy and paste text, and use\n"
"important vim extensions like visual mode and multi-window editing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you either don't know or aren't comfortable using vi, then you owe\n"
"it to yourself to take this tutorial and get up to speed with one of\n"
"the most popular and powerful Linux/UNIX visual editing programs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "About the guide"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There's one thing in particular that makes it difficult to learn vi --\n"
"vi has lots of commands. In order to use vi effectively, you need to\n"
"memorize quite a few. This can take a long time, and one of the goals\n"
"of this tutorial is not to take up a lot of your time. So, initially,\n"
"we have a challenge -- how exactly do I help you to memorize lots of\n"
"commands in a short period of time?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To tackle this challenge, as we proceed through this tutorial, we're\n"
"going to gradually put together a vi cheat sheet. This sheet will\n"
"contain all the important vi commands. After you've completed this\n"
"tutorial, you'll be able to refer to this cheat sheet if you forget a\n"
"particular command. Over time, as you memorize commands, you'll\n"
"gradually become less and less dependent on the cheat sheet. By using\n"
"the cheat-sheet technique, you'll be able to learn how to use vi\n"
"faster than ever possible before!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "The learning process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:80
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this guide, I'm going to use several techniques to help you\n"
"learn. First, I'm going to describe how a particular command works,\n"
"as you'd expect. Then, I'm going to ask you to try to use the command\n"
"in vi (for practice), and then I'm going to ask you to transcribe the\n"
"command to the cheat sheet (for later reference.) If you want to\n"
"learn vi quickly, it's important that you perform all these steps.\n"
"Trying out a command in vi and transcribing the command onto your\n"
"cheat sheet will help you to memorize the command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing vim"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:97
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are many versions of vi, and I'm going to be showing you how to\n"
"use a version of vi called <c>vim</c>. vim is very popular and has a\n"
"number of extensions that make vi a lot nicer (whenever I demonstrate\n"
"a vim-specific command, I'll make a note of it.) If you need to\n"
"install vim, you can get it from <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.vim.org/\">www.vim.org</uri>. In addition to an\n"
"enhanced command-line vi, vim also comes with <c>gvim</c>, a nice graphical\n"
"editor which can be configured to use the excellent GTK+ gui library.\n"
"Here's a gvim screenshot from my system:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><figure>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "VIM screenshot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're a vi newbie, try to get gvim running on your system. Using\n"
"vi from a gui can make things a bit easier for beginners.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "First Steps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "Pick a file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:126
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before using vi to edit files, you need to know how to use vi to move\n"
"around in a file. vi has a lot of movement commands, and we're going\n"
"to take a look at many of them. For this part of the tutorial, find\n"
"an unimportant text file and load it into vi by typing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "Loading a file into vi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:133
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>vi myfile.txt</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:137
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you have vim installed, type <c>vim myfile.txt</c>. If you'd prefer to\n"
"use gvim, type <c>gvim myfile.txt</c>. <path>myfile.txt</path> should be the\n"
"name of a text file on your system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:145
#, no-wrap
msgid "Inside vi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:149
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After vi loads, you should see a part of the text file you loaded\n"
"on your screen. Congratulations -- you're in vi! Unlike many\n"
"editors, when vi starts up, it is in a special mode called <e>command\n"
"mode</e>. This means that if you press <c>l</c>on the keyboard, instead of\n"
"inserting an <c>l</c> into the file at the current cursor position, the\n"
"cursor will move one character to the right instead. In command mode,\n"
"the characters on your keyboard are used to send commands to vi rather\n"
"than insert literal characters into the text. One of the most\n"
"essential types of commands are movement commands; let's take a look\n"
"at some.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:166
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moving around"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:168
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moving in vi, part 1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When in command mode, you can use the <c>h</c>,<c>j</c>,<c>k</c> and\n"
"<c>l</c> keys to move the cursor left, down, up and right\n"
"respectively. If you're using a modern version of vi, you can also\n"
"use the arrow keys for this purpose. The <c>h</c>,<c>j</c>,<c>k</c>\n"
"and <c>l</c> keys are handy because once you're comfortable with them,\n"
"you'll be able to move around in the file without moving your fingers\n"
"from the home keyboard row. Try using <c>h</c>,<c>j</c>,<c>k</c> and\n"
"<c>l</c> (and the arrow keys) to move around in the text file. Try\n"
"using <c>h</c> until you get to the beginning of a line. Notice that\n"
"vi doesn't allow you to \"wrap around\" to the previous line by hitting\n"
"<c>h</c> while you're on the first character. Likewise, you can't\n"
"\"wrap around\" to the next line by hitting <c>l</c> at the end of a\n"
"line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:190
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moving in vi, part 2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:194
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vi offers special shortcuts for jumping to the beginning or end of the\n"
"current line. You can press <c>0</c> (zero) to jump to the first\n"
"character of a line, and <c>$</c> to jump to the last character of the\n"
"line. Try 'em and see. Since vi has so many handy movement commands,\n"
"it makes a great \"pager\" (like the more or less commands.) Using vi\n"
"as a pager will also help you to learn all the movement commands very\n"
"quickly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:204
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also use <c>&lt;CTR&gt;F</c> and <c>&lt;CTR&gt;B</c> to move\n"
"forwards and backwards a page at a time. Modern versions of vi (like\n"
"vim) will also allow you to use the <c>PGUP</c> and <c>PGDOWN</c> keys for this\n"
"purpose.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:213
#, no-wrap
msgid "Word moves, part 1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:217
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vi also allows you to move to the left or right by word increments.\n"
"To move to the <e>first</e> character of the next word, press\n"
"<c>w</c>. To move to the <e>last</e> character of the next word,\n"
"press <c>e</c>. To move to the first character of the <e>previous</e>\n"
"word, press <c>b</c>. Test 'em out.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:227
#, no-wrap
msgid "Word moves, part 2"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:231
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After playing around with the word movement commands, you may have\n"
"noticed that vi considers words like <c>foo-bar-oni</c> as five separate\n"
"words! This is because by default, vi delimits words by spaces\n"
"<e>or</e> punctuation. <c>foo-bar-oni</c> is therefore considered five\n"
"words: <c>foo</c>, <c>-</c>, <c>bar</c>, <c>-</c> and <c>oni</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:239
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Sometimes, this is what you want, and sometimes it isn't.\n"
"Fortunately, vi also understands the concept of a \"bigword\". vi\n"
"delimits bigwords by <e>spaces or newlines only</e>. This means that\n"
"while <c>foo-bar-oni</c> is considered five vi words, it's considered only\n"
"one vi bigword.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:249
#, no-wrap
msgid "Word moves, part 3"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:253
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To jump around to the next and previous bigword, you can use a\n"
"<e>capitalized</e> word move command. Use <c>W</c> to jump to the\n"
"first character of the next bigword, <c>E</c> to jump to the last\n"
"character of the next bigword, and <c>B</c> to jump to the first\n"
"character of the previous bigword. Test 'em out, and compare the\n"
"matching word and bigword movement commands until you understand their\n"
"differences.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "Bigger moves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:269
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We just have a few more commands to cover before it's time to start\n"
"puting together our cheat sheet. You can use the <c>(</c> and\n"
"<c>)</c> characters to move to the beginning of the previous and next\n"
"sentence. In addition, you can hit <c>{</c> or <c>}</c> to jump to\n"
"the beginning of the current paragraph, and the beginning of the next.\n"
"Test 'em out.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:282
#, no-wrap
msgid "Quitting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:287
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've covered the basic movement commands, but there are another\n"
"couple of commands that you need to know. Typing <c>:q</c> will quit\n"
"vi. If this doesn't work, then you probably accidentally modified the\n"
"file in some way. To tell vi to quit, throwing away any changes, type\n"
"<c>:q!</c>. You should now be at the command prompt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:295
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In vi, any command that begins with a <c>:</c> is said to be an\n"
"<e>ex-mode</e> command. This is because vi has a built-in non-visual\n"
"editor called <e>ex</e>. It can be used similarly to sed to perform\n"
"line-based editing operations. In addition, it can also be used to\n"
"quit, as we've just seen. If you ever hit the <c>Q</c> key while in\n"
"command mode, you'll be transported to ex mode. If this ever happens\n"
"to you, you'll be confronted with a : prompt, and hitting enter will\n"
"scroll the entire screen upwards. To get back to good 'ol vi mode,\n"
"simply type vi and hit enter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:311
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Cheat Sheet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "The beginnings of the cheat sheet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:317
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've covered a lot of commands, and it's time to transcribe them to\n"
"our cheat sheet. For the cheat sheet, you'll need a US letter or A4\n"
"sized piece of paper (we're going to pack a lot of info onto this\n"
"sheet!) Here's a picture of my cheat sheet after I've transcribed all\n"
"the commands that we've covered so far. Try to follow my layout if\n"
"possible so that we can fit everything on one sheet.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><figure>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "Cheat Sheet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:331
#, no-wrap
msgid "Miscellaneous vi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:335
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's continue our rapid command-covering pace. In command-mode, you\n"
"can jump to a particularline by typing <c>G</c>. To jump to the first\n"
"line of a file, type <c>1G</c>. Note that <c>G</c> is capitalized.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:341
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you want to jump to the next occurence of a particular text\n"
"pattern, type <c>/&lt;regexp&gt;</c> and hit <c>enter</c>. Replace\n"
"&lt;regexp&gt; with the regular expression you're looking for. If you\n"
"don't know how to use regular expressions, don't fret -- typing\n"
"<c>/foo</c> will move to the next occurence of <e>foo</e>. The only\n"
"thing you'll need to watch out for is when you want to refer to the\n"
"literal <c>^</c>, <c>.</c>, <c>$</c> or <c>\\</c> characters. Prefix\n"
"these characters with a backslash (<c>\\</c>), and you'll be set. For\n"
"example, <c>/foo\\.gif</c> will search for the next occurence of\n"
"\"foo.gif\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:354
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To repeat the search forwards, hit <c>n</c>. To repeat the search\n"
"backwards, type <c>N</c>. As always, test these commands out in your\n"
"very own vi editor. You can also type <c>//</c> to repeat the last\n"
"search.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:365
#, no-wrap
msgid "Saving and Editing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:367
#, no-wrap
msgid "Save and save as..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:371
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've covered how you can use the <e>ex</e> command <c>:q</c> to quit\n"
"from vi. If you want to save your changes, type <c>:w</c>. If you\n"
"want to save your changes to another file, type <c>:w filename.txt</c>\n"
"to save as <e>filename.txt</e>. If you want to save and quit, type\n"
"<c>:x</c> or <c>:wq</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:379
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In vim (and other advanced vi editors, like elvis)<c>:w</c>, you can\n"
"have multiple buffers open at once. To open a file into a new window,\n"
"type <c>:sp filename.txt</c>. <path>filename.txt</path> will appear open\n"
"for editing in a new split window. To switch between windows, type\n"
"<c>&lt;CTR&gt;w&lt;CTR&gt;w</c> (control-w twice). Any <c>:q</c>,\n"
"<c>:q!</c>, <c>:w</c> and <c>:x</c> commands that you enter will only\n"
"be applied to the currently-active window.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:391
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simple edits"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:395
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, it's time to start learning some of the simple editing commands.\n"
"The commands that we'll cover here are considered <e>simple</e> because the\n"
"commands keep you in command mode. The more complex editing commands\n"
"automatically put you into insert mode -- a mode that allows you to\n"
"enter literal data from the keyboard. We'll cover those in a bit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:403
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For now, try moving over some characters and hitting <c>x</c>\n"
"repeatedly. You'll see that <c>x</c> will delete the current\n"
"character under the cursor. Now, move to the middle of the paragraph\n"
"somewhere in your text file, and hit <c>J</c> (capitalized). You'll\n"
"see that the <c>J</c> command tells vi to join the next line to the\n"
"end of the current line. Now, move over a character and hit\n"
"<c>r</c>, and then type in a new character; you'll see that the\n"
"original character has been replaced. Finally, move to any line in\n"
"the file and type <c>dd</c>. You'll see that <c>dd</c> deletes the\n"
"current line of text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "Repeating and deleting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:422
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can repeat any editing command by hitting the <c>.</c> key. If\n"
"you experiment, you'll see that typing <c>dd...</c> will delete 4\n"
"lines, and <c>J......</c> will join four lines. As usual, vi provides\n"
"with another handy shortcut.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:429
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To delete text, you can also use the <c>d</c> command combined with\n"
"any movement command. For example, <c>dw</c> will delete from the\n"
"current position to the beginning of the next word; <c>d)</c> will\n"
"delete up until the end of the next sentence, and <c>d}</c> will\n"
"delete the remainder of the paragraph. Experiment with the\n"
"<c>d</c> command and the other editing commands until you're\n"
"comfortable with them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:441
#, no-wrap
msgid "Undo!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:445
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that we're experimenting with deletion, it would be a good time to\n"
"learn how to undo any changes. By pressing <c>u</c>, the original\n"
"version of vi allowed you to undo the last edit only. However, modern\n"
"versions of vi like vim will allow you to repeatedly press <c>u</c> to\n"
"continue to undo changes to your file. Try combining some <c>d</c>\n"
"and <c>u</c> commands together.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:456 en/vi-guide.xml:588
#, no-wrap
msgid "Updating the cheat sheet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:460
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Time to update the cheat sheet! After adding all the commands we've\n"
"covered so far, your cheat sheet should look like this:\n"
msgstr ""

