#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:602
#, no-wrap
msgid "Productivity features"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:606
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So far, we've covered how to move, save and quit, perform simple edits\n"
"and deletions, and use insert mode. With everything listed on the\n"
"cheat sheet so far, you should be able to use vi to perform almost any\n"
"task.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:613
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, vi also has many more powerful commands. In this section,\n"
"you'll learn how to <e>cut</e>, <e>copy</e> and <e>paste</e>,\n"
"<e>search</e> and <e>replace</e>, and use <e>autoindent</e> features.\n"
"These commands will help make vi more fun and productive.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "Visual mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:626
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The best way to cut and paste is to use <e>visual mode</e>, a special mode that\n"
"has been added to modern versions of vi, like vim and elvis. You can think\n"
"of visual mode as a \"highlight text\" mode. Once the text is highlighted,\n"
"it can be copied or deleted, and then pasted. If you are using gvim, you\n"
"can highlight by simply dragging the left mouse button over a particular\n"
"region:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><figure>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:634
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"VIM\n"
"with highlighted text"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:638
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition, you can also enter visual mode by hitting <c>v</c> (this\n"
"may be your only option if you are using vi from the console.) Then,\n"
"by moving the cursor using movement commands (typically the arrow\n"
"keys), you'll be able to highlight a region of text. Once\n"
"highlighted, we are ready to cut or copy the text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:646
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're copying the text, hit <c>y</c> (which stands for \"yank\").\n"
"If you're cutting the text, hit <c>d</c>. You'll be placed back in\n"
"command mode. Now, move to the position where you'd like to insert\n"
"the cut or copied text, and hit <c>P</c> to insert before the cursor,\n"
"or <c>p</c> to insert after the cursor. Voila, the cut/copy and\n"
"paste is complete! Test out several copy/cut and paste operations\n"
"before advancing to the next section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:658
#, no-wrap
msgid "Replacing text"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:662
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To replace patterns of text, we use <e>ex</e> mode. If you'd like to\n"
"replace the first pattern that appears on the current line, type\n"
"<c>:s/&lt;regexp&gt;/&lt;replacement&gt;/</c> and hit\n"
"<c>&lt;ENTER&gt;</c>, where &lt;regexp&gt; is the pattern you'd like\n"
"to match and &lt;replacement&gt; is the replacement string. To\n"
"replace all matches on the current line, type\n"
"<c>:s/&lt;regexp&gt;/&lt;replacement&gt;/g</c> and hit enter. To\n"
"replace every occurence of this pattern in your file (normally what\n"
"you want), type <c>:%s/&lt;regexp&gt;/&lt;replacement&gt;/g</c>. If\n"
"you'd like to do a global replace, but have vi prompt you for each\n"
"change, type <c>:%s/&lt;regexp&gt;/&lt;replacement&gt;/gc</c> (stands\n"
"for \"confirm\") and hit <c>&lt;ENTER&gt;</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:679
#, no-wrap
msgid "Indentation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/vi-guide.xml:683
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vi supports autoindentation, for when you are editing source code.\n"
"Most modern versions of vi (like vim) will auto-enable autoindent mode\n"
"when you are editing a source file (like a .c file, for example).\n"
"When autoindent is enabled, you can use <c>&lt;CTR&gt;d</c>\n"
"(control-d) to move one indent level to the left, and\n"
"<c>&lt;CTR&gt;t</c> (control-t) to move one indent level to the right.\n"
"If autoindent wasn't enabled automatically, you can manually enable it\n"
"by typing in the <e>ex</e> command <c>:set autoindent</c>. You can\n"
"also tell vi to set the tab size to your favorite setting by using the\n"
"<c>:set tabstop</c> command; <c>:set tabstop=4</c> is quite popular.\n"
msgstr ""

